The first virtual service provider will reach the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe
The Czech mobile market is relatively advanced and our service providers offer the same services as their Western European partners.
Nevertheless, something is missing here - the virtual service provider that forces the classic service providers to significantly reduce prices.
Maybe it won't be like this for long.
We have already written on the Mobil.cz website that Czech service providers are among the most expensive in Europe.
This was also confirmed by ČTú, which drew attention to the fact that the price of texts in the Czech Republic is more expensive than in the other countries of the Union.
Following the last move of the European Commission to regulate roaming charges, perhaps there is a conflicting situation - the Czech mobile service providers will be cheaper than their domestic texts from abroad for some of their customers.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that really wants to fight.
This may sound controversial, since we have three mobile networks and our penetration is very high above 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators are happy to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
This is often agreed with the President of the Council of the Czech Telecoms Office, Pavel Dvoňák, who has previously said a few times that there is no newer service provider in the Czech Republic.
It may be true that the classic service provider is unlikely to have too many chances with its own network (although it would probably be difficult to find a frequency already).
But there is another option - the virtual service provider.
It was the move of virtual service providers to the mobile market that led to a significant fall in prices, which would then have had to be responded to by classic service providers.
Meanwhile, even before the big fish entered the market, sounds like ours were heard in Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile Great Britain.
However, it has been demonstrated that such service providers have a place and can indeed be successful.
However, we do not have to go too far for an example.
This February we briefed you on the launch of the Mobiling Virtual Service Provider in Poland.
In less than six months, this service provider was able to obtain more than 100 thousand customers and become the fifth largest service provider there.
In the meantime, behind Mobiling is the Penta Financial Group, which also owns the U-phone in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual service providers is the possibility of focusing on a much narrower target group.
Effective operation requires much less customers than the traditional service provider.
It does not entail relatively high costs of construction, mobile network operation and maintenance.
Virtual service providers in the world thus usually appear at low cost - offer cheap calls and text messages, which are often offset by fewer services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in Great Britain offers at least 50 percent cheaper text messages than its competitors.
But as shown by the example of Mobiling in Poland, it is a pretty good move for a target group.
This service provider focuses specifically on men.
"The real men choose the Mobiling service provider - who they like to trust," says David Seibert, CEO of the Mobil Entertainment Company, which operates this virtual service provider.
It's hard to tell if an idea like that in Poland can work with us.
Miroslav Čepický, spokesperson of Vodafone, doubts about this: "The Czech market is relatively small for a segmental approach, on which the majority of virtual service providers are based.
In addition, it is relatively satisfied with the provision of services."
In the Czech Republic, it is impossible for mobile operators to claim
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual service in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobiling.
"We are talking about the successful expansion of this project, but in the Czech Republic, the negotiations do not seem very hopeful.
The launch of Mobilking will take place in other countries in our region," said Jana Studničková, spokesperson of the Penta Financial Group in her phone interview with Mobil.cz.
By doing so, it demonstrated that the existing mobile service providers in the Czech Republic are not too much in sympathy with this idea.
On the contrary, they are trying to do their utmost to prevent any potential competition from being created.
The GTS Nevera Group has for some time been hiding its interest in the launch of the virtual service provider, which therefore intends to take another step towards making Telematica O2 a real competitor in the field of corporate customers.
"We are very interested in providing not only fixed but also mobile telecommunications services to our customers.
The sooner the better.
We have once again discussed this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
Some of them have already made progress in the negotiations," says Pavel Kaidl, the spokesperson of the group.
Maybe now's the best time.
From informal information, we seem to be lucky for the first virtual service provider by the end of the year.
But his birth is surrounded by the wall of impenetrable silence.
"In this moment, we do not believe that a fully-fledged virtual service provider would have a place in the Czech market.
Contrary to the other markets, the Czech market is very special.
So far, we have not been invited by a single subject offering a complex and serious project in this area," mentioned Vlastimil Sršeň, Telefónica 02 Press Department to Mobil.cz.
The special situation of the Czech market is also referred to by the other operators.
Martina Kemrová, T-Mobile's spokesperson, exceptionally agrees with O2: "So far we have not registered any viable and bilateral business projects that could be further founded on."
And he added, "The T-Mobile network is unlikely to show up at the end of the year with any virtual service provider.
At this point, we should have a specific agreement on our table so that we can think so in the short term."
Vodafone’s attention is more focused on meeting its 3G licence requirements.
Miroslav Čepický adds: "We are open to negotiation with potential virtual service providers, especially in the area of sharing costs and infrastructure.
This is what we consider to be the most cost-effective for our clients.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to partner in the construction of high-speed mobile internet-sharing networks."
Responsible offices - a string with service providers
The procedure of mobile operators is easy to understand, and the entry of another provider would lead to an increase in competition, a reduction in prices and thus a decrease in their profits.
So why make it easier for us to enter such a competition?
When service providers are able to cooperate, they are also able to testify about the u:phone being born.
The highest pressure on ČTÜ is likely to be around the birth of the U-phone of the T-Mobile company.
This is evidenced by publicly available information on the ČTU website.
But right now it's on the U phone as a good reason why we don't allow the virtual service provider to enter.
Martina Kemrová added: "The environment of competition in the mobile market has recently been affected by access to the fourth mobile market.
Given the nature of the Czech mobile market, it is obvious that the entry of another player into the market and its services would be subject to high requirements."
However, given the attitude of mobile operators, the total lack of interest of the Czech regulators is absolutely amazing.
In the meantime, it is not only about ČTU's attitude, which unfortunately, in the Czech Republic, unlike Great Britain and other developed countries, has no right to intervene in economic competition.
Only the Economic Competition Authority has the right to do so.
However, the Office is typical of the whole problem.
"The entry into the mobile market of a virtual service provider would only be possible after the conclusion of a contract between the mobile service provider and the virtual service provider for the leasing of the necessary infrastructure.
No such contract has been concluded so far, since the offer of potential interested parties was probably not sufficiently interesting for traditional service providers," said Kristián Chlapua, in response to our question about the External Relations Department of the Economic Competition Agency.
A statement made by the representatives of the service providers would probably not surprise anyone.
However, from an agency which should represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, be careful not to allow anyone to recover from their market situation, it is more than strange.
In particular, if Kristián Chalupa adds: "In a foreign country where virtual service providers generally operate, we can see that their entry into the market has contributed to the reduction in the price of mobile phone services."
However, UOHS's interests are likely not to be affected by the pressure on the proper functioning of the market environment and the fall in prices.
In this case, it is indeed shocking that the reaction of the three mobile operators is a very tangible line.
The question is, is it really just a coincidence? It's almost self-evident.
As in the charging stations, the exact same fuel prices are probably just the works of chance and hard competition.
"The Office has not discovered the signs of anticompetitive proceedings in this case, so there is no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the service providers has a leading position, i.e. a proportionately higher responsibility for market facts.
The tools needed to open up the mobile market for virtual service providers are likely to be lacking by the telecommunications regulator," said Chalupa.
The presentation of the market leadership situation is one of the many points of debate.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by ČTú, on the basis of which telecommunications is the only market from the point of view of economic competition.
There is, of course, no Czech service provider in such a market.
However, some legal experts offer a different approach - the creation of a virtual service provider always requires the approval of the network operator.
And the mobile service provider, relatively logically, has a monopoly on its own network.
So it is necessarily dominant in a particular segment.
But even if we did not accept this argument, it should be minimal for UOHS to have three mobile operators act in a similar way.
Meanwhile, complaints from interested parties (including the previously mentioned GTS Nevera company) show that they face very similar obstacles during negotiations with all service providers.
And putting responsibility on ČTú is a relatively common trick in telecommunications, with which the UOHS will take his hand off the whole matter.
We've seen this in a few similar situations.
Unfortunately, in the text of the recently adopted Telecommunications Act, the extension of the mandate of ČTÜ in the field of economic competition could not be achieved in telecommunications, although many experts hoped to improve the situation.
The UOHS representatives need to know this well, but they probably have different interests.
It works when no one's watching.
At the same time, the operation of some kind of fake virtual service provider remains unnoticed, many of which are already operating in the Czech mobile networks.
These are companies that issue their own mobile phone service price lists, but which are only partially public.
It's multilevel marketing companies.
For example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
The price lists of these companies usually only reach the selected ones.
The magic lies in the fact that the company acts as a classic corporate customer against the provider, which orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As a prominent customer, you will receive special offers (and other discounts).
The problem is that all Czech mobile operators are prohibited from making similar reservations.
"If there were cases of breaches of the terms of the contract that we would be dealing with and which could lead to the end of cooperation with the company," Martina Kemrová answered our question about this problem.
But it is unlikely that the news of such activities would not have reached the people responsible for mobile operators.
In particular, thousands of customers may be involved in the three companies mentioned.
At the same time, no service provider defends against such a procedure.
These companies have non-minor profits and, unlike the real virtual service providers, do not, in particular, threaten their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns against possible problems: "The law allows similar speculations, however, the services of these companies are only used by a negligible percentage of customers.
They must also accept that the SIM card is not listed on their phone, so they cannot have it fully as general customers of mobile service providers."
But at least that's what ČTú should be weird about.
In addition, another question arises for UOHS.
If mobile service providers ignore a similar procedure, why do they prevent the birth of a virtual service provider?
It should be added that the UOHS has relatively strong powers to reveal such activity and, if it does not want to, it does not have to be satisfied with the explanation of the service providers that they did not suspect such a thing and that their trading conditions prohibit it.
♪ When we don't get the most expensive ♪
As has already been said in the text a few times, the entry of virtual service providers into the mobile market has led to a appreciable reduction in the price of services.
In the meantime, in virtually all countries where virtual service providers were established, classical service providers have tried to prevent their creation more or less.
The arguments they used were practically the same - too small, perhaps too satisfied, problems with the quality of services, etc.
However, in the developed countries, regulators intervened at these moments, which in no way protected the interests of mobile operators, but of their customers.
Then, either by formal measures or by informal pressure, they achieved the creation of the first virtual service provider followed by others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators are giving the whole thing to each other.
Based on our experience, we can't get rid of the impression that their unclear competences are good for them in these cases.
But let's not give up the fight.
If the background information is good and the virtual service provider is very soon present, the Czech mobile market may start to move again.
If one of the service providers would allow the creation of a virtual mobile service provider, the UOHS would only be difficult to be indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And perhaps, compared to the rest of Europe, we will no longer make more expensive calls.
