The Prague Transport Company also delivers chips for the first time on Wednesday
Wednesday, 1 October 2008 sign in to the history of the Prague Transport Company when the first passenger enters the metros, trams and buses, who will have an electronic coupon in his pocket instead of a paper line.
The coupon is currently available for about 100,000 people with the Opencard chip card.
Passengers can buy a 30-day and 90-day and annual coupons (which will be valid from 1 January 2009) and can also save their chips at the information centers and offices of the Transport Company at the metro stations of Muzeum, M.Stek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
The coupons can be purchased online from yesterday via the Transport Company www.dpp.cz website.
The service was used by more than 400 customers until the afternoon hours.
Those who start using Internet commerce can ultimately forget the publishing windows at the metro stations, where they have had to make regular lines for tickets.
The coupon can be purchased over the internet and stored on the Opencard card in one of the thirteen branches of the City Library.
"In these places, passengers have a counter with trained servers to help interested parties buy online and save their purchased coupons on their cards," said Martin Opatrný, the project coordinator.
In addition to the libraries, the electronic coupons can be saved to the Opencard in the self-service machines provided in some halls.
What do these machines look like?
Red, reminds me of the ticket operators, and the passengers may already have noticed them at Roztyly, Budějovicka, I.P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská metro stations.
"There are currently five of them in the city, but it should be 80 by the end of the year," added Opatrný.
The coupon checks automatically instead of the driver
It's easy to handle machines that start tomorrow.
It's enough to just insert the Opencard chip card and the coupon you paid earlier will be saved by yourself.
The electronic coupons will be valid not only in the capital from tomorrow, but also in its vicinity.
So on trains and bus routes around the city, from 300 to 499, with which the residents of the Central-Czech tours mainly travel to the capital.
"On the Prague Integrated Traffic trains, the guide has been provided with card readers to help establish the zone validity of the coupons," explained Philip Drápal, who has prepared the Prague Public Transport Agenda.
In the buses around the city, the card readers at the driver's office are built in the cash register.
The driver must therefore not only show the chip card on the way in, but also place the Opencard in the location specified on the cashier's side.
This is how the driver checks the validity of the coupons.
"If, for example, the passenger needs to check the validity of the coupons, it is easiest to ask the driver to do so," Dravel added.
Passengers who do not travel by bus around the city and who will not remember when their coupon expires can once again go to self-service machines that save coupons.
The information on the validity of their documents is displayed here on the display of the equipment.
