Blood is safe again
Hema-Québec celebrated the tenth anniversary of his foundation yesterday. President Francine Décary had good reason to celebrate because Hema-Québec has become one of the world's safest and most effective blood-staining societies.
The most important thing is that he managed to regain people's trust, which was severely shaken by the scandal of blood infection in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, national blood reserves treated by the Canadian Red Cross blood service were infected with acquired immune deficiency syndrome (HIV) and hepatitis C viruses in the 1980s.
Following the drama and the general upheaval, in February 1994, the Canadian Government launched a formal investigation under the leadership of Judge Horace Krever, which was intended to shed light on the circumstances that led to the tragedy and to make proposals to avoid future similar cases.
While Judge Krever's late report was submitted, some provinces set up their own committee to plan a new blood management system for Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee fulfilled this task.
Following the Gélineau and Krever reports, two blood services were established in Canada: one was Hema-Québec, serving Quebec, and the other was the Canadian Blood Protection Company responsible for all other provinces and two territories.
"When Hema-Québec started his activity in 1998, almost 38% of people had confidence in Quebec's blood supply system," recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was desperate.
"In the coming years, however, as a result of our work in the field, we managed to regain people's trust." Hema-Québec was proud to declare that at the beginning of 2008 nearly 94% of the population in Quebec believed that hema-Québec was reliable.
But Dr. Décary doesn't forget that "trust is an extremely fragile thing".
Since its establishment on 28 September 1998, Hema-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
During this period, a number of cases have been revealed in Europe where the new variants of the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease have infected people, says the doctor, who has been managing the company since its establishment in 1998.
"We had no idea if this disease was spreading by blood.
We therefore relied on one of the most important recommendations in the Krever and Gélineau reports, which means that if we are uncertain about this and there is a risk of developing a serious disease, we must take exclusion measures. In this case, Creutzfeldt-Jakob's disease, which causes the brain to change, inevitably leads to death.
Therefore, in April 1999, we did not accept blood from people who have spent more than a month in the United Kingdom since 1980.
And a few years ago, it was unmistakably established that the disease was spreading by blood.
This case convinced us that it made sense to apply the precautionary principle."
In 1999, a technique appeared in the market that allows a much more sensitive diagnosis of the HIV virus. This is a nucleic acid test (NAT), which is capable of directly detecting the virus itself in the blood of blood donors, rather than antibodies to the virus on which the previously used tests were based.
With the help of the NAT test, we could shorten the window period from infection until the virus can be detected in the blood using our technical tools, explains the expert.
This period could be reduced for a period of less than one week.
Thus, they significantly reduced the risk of blood transfusions not only being known but also that this could not be shown.
These developments greatly reduced the risk of AIDS being transmitted by blood transfusions.
Today, there is a risk that someone will be infected with the HIV virus, with 12 million to one.
"In other words, it means that we should distribute 12 million blood products until someone is infected with the HIV virus.
Since Hema-Québec distributes between 400 and 500 thousand blood products every year, it would take more than 24 years for such a case to occur and for someone to be infected with HIV through a blood product.
I think that anyone today can accept or write blood transfusions to restore health, says Hema-Québec's number one leader.
"The challenge for the next decade will be to maintain the reliability of our products.
We never know what new pathogen is entering the system.
It was only last year that the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, can enter the blood with insect bites.
Therefore, we must be constantly alert," said Dr. Décary, and then stressed that, apart from the emergency reserves, Hema-Québec must provide sufficient permanent reserves.
"Aging the population also increases demands.
Because anticancer treatments have become more aggressive, patients often need to replace red blood cells or platelets.
Population ageing has an impact on blood donors, as the number of people in the network who can donate blood accounts for only 3% of the population in Quebec.
However, every healthy person aged at least 18 years who fulfils the eligibility criteria can give blood every 56 days, i.e. six times a year.
On average, 14% of applicants do not accept blood because they are infected with AIDS or malaria, for example, and those who have been in a country where malaria destroys are not eligible for blood for a year.
"With this 3 percent we have enough reserves to meet the needs of the hospitals.
It's very rare for us to run out of supplies.
However, we need to increase the number of blood donors to the extent that existing ones grow older because they can't give blood after a while.
However, it is very difficult to convince people to give blood, but it is even more difficult to keep them and make them become regular donors.
In today's rushing world, man has barely an hour to go to give blood" - regrets Francine Décary.
Hema-Québec, a $297 million annual budget, provides not only blood products but also human tissues, such as bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs and skin tissue, which are used almost exclusively for severely burned individuals.
These tissues are analysed, transformed and frozen, and then placed at the Hema-Québec, which also manages a single public stem cell bank in Quebec.
The hair can only be obtained from a cord treated as medical waste from a cord that is rich in stem cells, thus enabling the treatment of serious diseases (e.g. leukaemia).
"We celebrated a few weeks ago that we had entered our bank for the thousandth cord blood sample, and we plan to remove more than a thousand new samples every year.
At the beginning of next year, we are probably starting to offer these for organ transplants," said Dr. Décary, who said that the cord-line-reduction program is very popular these days.
"Many moms are sad that they can't do that" - that's true, because Hema-Québec has no way of making this complex and costly program available in every hospital in Quebec.
