The 700 billion US dollars plan aimed at curbing the financial crisis on Wall Street for months still needs to be approved by the two houses of Congress.
Key points of the plan: to monitor implementation more effectively by Members; new mechanisms to ensure that public money is repaid; new provisions to keep the number of houses occupied due to non-payments; access to the payment of managers of assisted companies.
Henry Paulson, U.S. Minister of Finance, Nancy Pelosi, President of the American Chamber of Representatives, and Judd Gregg, the Republican representative in the trial yesterday, announced the good news a few minutes before midnight after the two-day marathon trial.
"We have made great progress towards a solution that will work effectively in the markets," said Henry Paulson, a representative of the Bush Government.
"We have done everything we can to save the real economy and American citizens from the current crisis on Wall Street," explained the Democrat Representative.
"The most important point is that if we don't do this, then the shock, chaos and confusion in the American everyday lives will be enormous," said Judd Gregg, Republican MP.
The trial was speeded up in the last few hours, fearing that another failure would adversely affect the mood of investors.
The agreement was given a deadline until this morning's opening of the stock exchange.
The two presidential candidates who joined the negotiations late showed their willingness to reach an agreement, however, they were not happy that the situation was increasing to the end.
Senator Barack Obama has attributed to himself the extension of the agreement with elements such as provisions relating to the preservation of house-ownership or the payment of directors of companies assisted by the State.
"When we ask taxpayers to take certain extraordinary steps because of the irresponsibility of other people, it is not too enjoyable.
These steps, however, are necessary," he noted on an American television show.
When John McCain asked if he would vote for the proposed plan, he replied: "I would like to know the details, but I hope so."
"What I have read in large lines is evident from the fact that it is something that we all need to digest and move on.
The possibility of not doing anything is simply unacceptable," he said.
According to the $700 billion plan, taxpayers' money would buy the suspicious claims of American financial institutions, some unsold assets at risk.
The plan was preceded by a 14-month crisis triggered by the collapse of the real estate register. This led first to the collapse of risky real estate loans (secondary mortgage loans) and then to the spread of other (commercial) debt securities, resulting in the freezing of liquid resources and the fragility of banks and financial institutions.
The first draft agreement was failed by a group of Republican Members last week.
It seems that we have been able to get out of this dead end since the Democrats have agreed to ensure that certain "toxic" assets of companies in difficulty are provided by the government rather than by the government.
In order to be satisfied with all the members of Congress, a provision has been included in the plan which provides that if the government has to bear losses within the programme for five years, it may levy new taxes to recover its resources.
As part of the new plan, a 250 billion-dollar instalment would be paid for the first time; it could be followed by an additional 100 billion if the President deems it necessary.
The remaining $350 billion should be approved by Congress by another vote.
In exchange for the aid, Washington will acquire a share in the supported companies, through which it will receive dividends from profits and which it can sell after the crisis has resolved.
The Federal Government will have the opportunity to delay the seizure of real estate to cover the mortgage loans covered by the plan, and may also set a maximum value for remuneration and pay for the management of companies affected by the crisis.
The plan makers would like the plan to be voted by the House of Representatives today and the Senate on Wednesday.
However, despite their efforts, the plan is still not yet approved.
Yesterday, the opposition to the plan has been repeated among both the Republicans and the Democrats.
"It is perfectly clear that Washington will not hear your voice," declared Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House's Financial Committee.
"Yes, we have serious financial problems.
Yes, there are solutions.
But there's no one that would benefit taxpayers."
Brad Sherman, the Democrat Member who led the small assembly group called the 'sceptical Group', is presenting things differently, but it comes to the same conclusion.
"Four hundred excellent economic experts, including three Nobel Prize-winning scientists, wrote to us to ask Congress: do not hurry and look closely at which path to choose," Sherman said yesterday.
In Europe, at the same time, it was once again understood that this was a global crisis.
After a crisis meeting, the three Benelux states announced that they would nationalise part of the Fortis banking group to a value of EUR 11.2 billion (16.3 billion).
The intervention by the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg became necessary after the French BNP Paribas announced that it would not buy its competitors on the verge of bankruptcy after losing EUR 2 million (EUR 2.9 billion) as a result of the US secondary mortgage crisis.
Fortis with 85 000 employees is one of the twenty largest European banks and the ten largest insurance companies.
"It's not thrown away money," said Dutch finance minister Wouter Bos yesterday.
"In exchange, we acquire voting rights and influence in the bank.
This is exactly what depositors and households greatly appreciate now that the situation promises to be uncertain."
Meanwhile, across La Manche, the British government seems to be preparing to nationalise another bank that has been driven away by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government would take over the total amount of ongoing loans from Bradford and Bringley Bank, of which real estate loans amount to £41 billion ($75.5 billion).
The Spanish bank Santander announced yesterday that they would buy the British bank's subsidiaries and client stocks.
Bradford and Bringley would be the second bank that the British government has wanted to publicise since the start of the crisis after Northern Rock.
