The psychology of over-licitation: why are we giving out more money?
In the auctions, buyers tend to issue more money, overvalue the goods.
The neurological-economic foundations of this known - and seemingly irrational - behavior have been revealed to neurologists and economists at the University of New York.
According to their study in Science magazine, people do not want to miss a type of competition, such as the eBay auction, so they pay too much.
The research tried to map this "play" nervous system scheme using experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers lotteryd, the other group participated in the player auction while the active brain areas of the experimental subjects were examined using the functional magnetic resonance (fMRI) method.
In both games, the participants could win money, but during the auction game - in which the over-licitation of the other party is an essential element - the stritaum under the cortex became active intensively when the game was lost.
This brain space plays a role in the mechanism of the nervous system "remuneration" in addition to several other functions.
Researchers therefore believe that the price rise can be explained by avoiding a sharp reaction to the striatium.
In support of their theory, the members of the economic operator of the research group also carried out financial follow-up studies.
In this, three groups bid against one partner under different circumstances.
The control group was simply informed of the real value of the product concerned and made their bets.
In addition, another group was promised that if they were to get out of the game, they would receive another $15.
The third group, on the other hand, received 15 dollars before the auction, but the members of the group lost this money in the event of the loss of the auction.
The difference between the two groups, therefore, was all that was emphasised for one of them to win, and for the other to lose.
However, by proving the hypothesis of neurologists, the members of the team playing against "loss" were willing to bet higher than the control and win group.
"These results cannot be derived from any pre-existing economic theory.
To date, they have only explained the events of the auction with the joy of victory and risk avoidance.
Only the neurological imaging methods helped to solve the contradiction between these two theories, and now we have a third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, Professor of Economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When should we consult a doctor?
Around half a billion people in the world suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary chronic liver disease is mentioned among the leading causes of death.
Hundreds of thousands of people are infected at home, but only seven thousand are treated, which is why patients often do not know that they are infected.
The designation of hepatitis is the common name of the liver problems caused by different viruses.
Their symptoms are of many similarities, characterised by inflammation of the liver and jaundice, but their pathogens and the diseases caused are different.
Hepatitis viruses are spread in two main forms depending on the pathogen: hepatitis A and E via the food canal (e.g. infected food, water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and body fluids (conjunctival, vaginal fluid, saliva).
Travellers should definitely be vaccinated against the A and B viruses, with no vaccine against C.
Hepatitis Symptoms occur between two and three weeks after the infected food is consumed, generally feeling unwell, weakness, abdominal complaint, with nausea.
After these develops yellowing on the skin and on the whites of the eyes, the stools are clear, the urine becomes dark and healing can take two or three weeks.
A million people a year die from a more severe disease in the world, liver cancer caused by hepatitis B, and liver cancer.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only one in ten infected people will receive medication.
Hepatitis C may also have very serious consequences: if not treated, it may lead to hepatic contraction and liver cancer.
Most infected people don't even know about their disease, because the pathogen subtly destroys the liver cells, in many cases only 20-30 years from now the first symptoms will occur.
Early prevention and regular screening are therefore very important.
In three groups, there are far more than average cases of such illness: people who have undergone blood transfusions before 1991, drug users and tattoos.
The world currently has 200 million people infected with the chronic hepatitis C virus.
Since the disease may already be detected by a routine laboratory test, it is advisable to seek medical advice if any symptoms of unknown origin are detected.
Recognizing the disease in time can be cured, the virus can be removed from the body, thus eliminating the potential for infection and preventing cancer from developing.
September 30th is the World Day of Hepatitis, which was the first organised in 2004 by patient organisations around the world.
Its purpose is to draw attention to chronic hepatitis caused by viruses, the causes of their development and the importance of early detection of the disease.
