The Dongo Flight Implicated by the Intelligent Car
What would be the best way to develop technologies to avoid collision if it were not to imitate barriers in the world of nature?
For example, bees.
In the surprising project at CEATEC, in Japan, the dongo bees gave the strategic idea to the engineers of Nissan to build the next generation of conflict prevention systems.
In cooperation with the University of Tokyo, Nissan built the BR23C bio-replicated car robot control system, a robotised mini-car, which was equipped with the properties of bees, with the ultimate aim of contributing to the development of a system that eliminates all collisions.
While flying, each bee develops its own oval-shaped personal space, which is in fact very similar to our safety cover - explained Kazuhhiro Doi at the exhibition, technological PR- and R & D brand director.
The role of the complex eye of the uterus is important, which can be seen in all directions at more than 300 degrees angles.
To copy the complex eye function, engineers reached out to the idea of a laser telescope.
It identifies obstacles within a distance of 2 m at a distance of 180 degrees at BR23C, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which immediately turns into an action to avoid impact.
During the fraction of the second, the obstacle is detected, and then the car robot, mimicking the movement of the uterus, changes the direction immediately by turning its wheels to the extent necessary to avoid impact.
In any way other than the current system, this avoiding manoeuvre is performed in a completely intuitive way.
"If this were not the case, the car robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, the head of the Mobility Laboratory and the car robot project.
Incentive and immediate response, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and internal layer of safety shields, a layer within which the collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what a bee does in order to avoid other bees.
This process should take place in a moment.
However, in a way other than bees, the deviation should not be directed upwards, downwards or transversely, only in two-dimensional directions, and only in the direction of rotation of the wheels.
In this way, instead of the infinite possibility available to bees to avoid other bees, only rotational movement and acceleration, as well as deceleration, have been used as an option for car robot.
BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are easier and have a higher energy density, which means that they have a longer life span than the lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, the intellectual intelligence response is important, not the ability to process and store data even less.
This device only needs to process and respond to a few input signals per second.
There is no need to preserve them and react with intuitive logic based on previous manoeuvring data, so it uses only a few dozen kilobytes of memory.
There's no need for gigabytes or megabytes of memory.
This is the first step towards the development of the immediate escape technology, which, based on Nissan's estimate, could be involved in serial cars within 10 years.
The integration of the unit with the GPS-satellite navigation system may be an additional application to prevent obstacles on the road leading the car to the specified end goal.
