Domestic sales prices of the industry increased by 0.1 per cent in August 2008 compared to the previous month, by 12.9 per cent compared to August 2007, according to KSH.
The prices of export sales to industry were 1.1 per cent higher than in July 2008, with a decrease of 3.9 per cent from one year earlier.
As a result of domestic and export price changes, industrial producer prices were 0.7 per cent higher than in the previous month and 3.2 per cent higher than one year earlier.
Domestic sales prices of the industry increased only to a minimum of 0.1 per cent compared to the previous month.
Domestic sales prices in manufacturing industries also increased slightly by 0.1 per cent compared to July.
The biggest increase in prices occurred in August 2008 in the leather product sector (2.8%), mainly due to a price increase of 4.6% in the production of bags, straps and 2.5% in the production of footwear per month.
The higher price level of plastic and chemical materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in the production of the chemical, product, at the prices of the industry (1.6%).
There was a fall in the price of oil processing (1.4 percent), electric machinery, instrument production (0.9 percent) and, to a minimum, wood processing (0.1 percent).
The prices of paper production, publishers and printing activities have not changed.
In the other manufacturing sectors, we measured a price increase of 0.2 per cent to 0.9 per cent.
In the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors, which represent a significant weight in domestic sales of the industry, prices increased by 0.3% in August, in particular as a result of the long-term impact of the official gas price increase carried out from 1 July.
In a 12-month comparison, prices increased most in the oil processing sector (32.4 per cent) in terms of domestic sales of the processing industries.
The production of metal-processing products in the sector was accompanied by an increase of 13.2 percent in the price of food, drink and tobacco production, representing a major weight.
The decrease in prices occurred in the textile, textile (2.5 percent) and electrical machinery and instrument production (0.3 percent).
In other manufacturing sectors, the rate of price increase ranged from 0.6 per cent to 9.1 per cent.
Prices have increased by 10.2 per cent over the last year in the manufacturing industry as a whole.
Prices in the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors exceeded 18.7% of the previous one year.
In domestic sales, among the target groups in the sectors, the highest monthly price increase (0.7 per cent) was seen in the sector producing investment goods in August.
In the consumer product industries, prices have increased by 0.3 per cent, and in the energy and downstream sectors, prices have not changed compared to the previous month.
Compared to the same month of the previous year, in August 2008, the largest price increase was observed in energy and downstream sectors (16.8%).
In the consumer goods sector, we measured a 6.8 per cent increase in prices, a 1.4 per cent decrease in investment goods.
The export sales prices of the industry in Forint increased by 1.1 per cent in August compared to the previous month and decreased by 3.9 per cent in 12 months.
