The energy comes from the waves, and now the big ones come.
An inexhaustible energy source that accounts for 70% of the planet's surface, which is only now being discovered by large international energy companies.
Waves, sea currents, tides, all renewable energy sources, for which giants like Chevron are now trying to put their hands on it.
For hundreds of years, they have been searching for ways to gain energy from the movements of the sea. In the 1970s, during the first oil crisis, research increased.
Around 1980, when oil prices decreased, the idea of using marine energy was discarded, but today the recovery of environmental demands and oil prices gives the industry new impetus.
According to the World Energy Council (WEC) of London in 2007, 15% of the world's electricity needs could be covered by marine wave recovery facilities.
This quantity is twice what nuclear power plants are currently producing.
In addition, the currents and the tide would be there.
The giants are on the ground.
Enersis was the first company to commit itself to marine energy and to sign an agreement in 2005 on a power plant in northern Portugal.
It seemed like a revolutionary move when the signature was announced.
Two years have passed since then, and more and more companies are voting for marine energy, including those who have been committed to traditional energy so far.
"Chevron is researching ocean energy technologies and considering the possibility of cooperation with us," stated one of the associated companies of the American oil industry giant, Wall Street Journal.
The cooperation in question concerns the acquisition of an authorisation for the launch of a project in Alaska for the exploitation of marine energy issued by the US Energy Committee.
This is not a minor matter, especially in view of the fact that the US is in the process of oil extraction in Alaska, and even President Bush has recently launched a plan for further drilling.
Besides Chevron, Verdant Power Inc., New York and Ocean Power, New Jersey, are also on the road to energy from the sea. The amounts invested so far, as far as you can see, are evidence of increasing interest.
Technology is waiting for development.
According to the experts, it is still an initial technology, only because the energy from the sea does not dispel the doubts about the environmental impact.
Existing facilities such as Portugal or Scotland are all small and therefore do not cause too much problems with the ecosystem.
However, in order to produce more energy on a larger scale, it is necessary to have facilities that have a more significant environmental impact.
There are several options: Ocean Power, for example, uses a connected boja system.
The shocks generated by the waves and moving the bushes up and down are turned into hydraulic pressure by the plungers and cylinders placed in them.
The pressure is turning a turbine, which feeds a generator.
The electric current goes to land on cable underground.
There are currently four similar types of facilities in the planning phase, which are only waiting for a federal permit. Some of the energy produced would be used in a military facility.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, has already started producing energy for a shopping mall and a parking lot using six sub-marine turbines located in the East River in New York.
When the water is running, the motion of the turbines rotates the shovels, and this rotation feeds the generator.
Verdant said that he had a long list of partners waiting only for permission to use energy.
Waves after tides.
At present, special attention is needed to make use of the opportunities available through the flood.
Although it is a periodic phenomenon, the tide is more predictable than wind, sun or waves, and therefore can be considered a more reliable source of energy.
New York, Maine and Alaska, as well as other coastal states spent $7.5 million in 2008, precisely to exploit the energy supplied by the tide, which is expected to grow to $35 million in 2009.
